---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro'
---

<Layout title="Claude Code 101 — From Prompting to Orchestrating | Pablo Suzarte" description="A hands-on workshop to take anyone from zero to orchestrating AI agents with Claude Code in terminal. Accessible and beginner-friendly." lang="en">
  <header class="ws-nav">
    <div class="ws-nav-inner">
      <a href="/how-i-build-with-ai" class="nav-back">&larr; AI School</a>
      <a href="/" class="nav-logo">PS</a>
      <span class="nav-breadcrumb">Workshop</span>
    </div>
  </header>

  <main id="main-content">
    <article class="ws">
      <!-- HERO -->
      <section class="ws-hero">
        <div class="ws-container">
          <p class="ws-kicker">For beginners and beyond</p>
          <h1 class="ws-title">Claude Code 101</h1>
          <p class="ws-subtitle">From asking a chatbot to orchestrating an agent that understands your world.</p>
          <div class="ws-meta-row">
            <div class="ws-meta-item">
              <span class="ws-meta-label">Duration</span>
              <span class="ws-meta-value">3–4 hours</span>
            </div>
            <div class="ws-meta-item">
              <span class="ws-meta-label">Level</span>
              <span class="ws-meta-value">Zero to Orchestrator</span>
            </div>
            <div class="ws-meta-item">
              <span class="ws-meta-label">Focus</span>
              <span class="ws-meta-value">The "AI Brain" Loop</span>
            </div>
            <div class="ws-meta-item">
              <span class="ws-meta-label">Goal</span>
              <span class="ws-meta-value">Your own AI workspace</span>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- INTRO -->
      <section class="ws-section">
        <div class="ws-container">
          <div class="ws-intro-grid">
            <div class="ws-intro-text">
              <h2 class="ws-section-title">What is this?</h2>
              <div class="ws-body">
                <p>Most AI experiences happen in a browser. You paste code, get a suggestion, and paste it back. That is <strong>prompting</strong>.</p>
                <p>Claude Code is different. It is a tool that lives <em>inside</em> your computer's terminal. It doesn't just talk; it <strong>acts</strong>. It can read your files, run your tests, and build your projects alongside you.</p>
                <p>This workshop is a slow, step-by-step journey for anyone—even if you've never used a terminal before.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="ws-intro-card">
              <h3>The Transformation</h3>
              <div class="ws-trans-step"><span>01</span> <strong>Prompting:</strong> Using AI as an oracle.</div>
              <div class="ws-trans-arrow">&darr;</div>
              <div class="ws-trans-step"><span>02</span> <strong>Collaborating:</strong> Using AI as a peer.</div>
              <div class="ws-trans-arrow">&darr;</div>
              <div class="ws-trans-step ws-trans-step--active"><span>03</span> <strong>Orchestrating:</strong> Designing a mind.</div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- MODULE 00: THE BRAIN -->
      <section class="ws-section ws-section--alt">
        <div class="ws-container">
          <p class="ws-section-num">00</p>
          <h2 class="ws-section-title">The Brain — how she thinks</h2>
          <p class="ws-principle-tag">Mental Model: To work with an agent, you must understand its loop.</p>
          <div class="ws-body">
            <p>Unlike a standard chatbot, Claude Code operates in a continuous loop. I call this the <strong>"Agentic Brain"</strong>.</p>
            
            <div class="ws-brain-loop">
              <div class="ws-loop-node">
                <strong>Observe</strong>
                <span>She reads your files and scans your project.</span>
              </div>
              <div class="ws-loop-node">
                <strong>Think</strong>
                <span>She reasons about your request vs the reality of the code.</span>
              </div>
              <div class="ws-loop-node">
                <strong>Act</strong>
                <span>She uses tools to edit files, run bash, or search content.</span>
              </div>
              <div class="ws-loop-node">
                <strong>Reflect</strong>
                <span>She checks the result and adjusts her next move.</span>
              </div>
            </div>

            <h3>The Architect and the Builder</h3>
            <p>Imagine you have two people in your terminal: an <strong>Architect</strong> who understands the big picture and a <strong>Builder</strong> who has all the tools. Claude Code is both.</p>
            <p>Your job isn't to tell the Builder "write line 42". Your job is to tell the Architect: "Here is our goal. Help me get there."</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

    <!-- PRE-REQUISITES -->
    <section class="ws-section">
      <div class="ws-container">
        <p class="ws-section-num">Setup</p>
        <h2 class="ws-section-title">Before the journey starts</h2>
        <div class="ws-body">
          <p>We need to prepare your environment. If any of these sound intimidating, don't worry—most only take a few seconds to verify.</p>
          
          <div class="ws-checklist">
            <div class="ws-check">
              <span class="ws-check-box">&#9744;</span>
              <div>
                <strong>Node.js 22+</strong> — The engine that runs Claude Code.
                <div class="ws-check-why">Verify: <code>node --version</code> in your terminal.</div>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="ws-check">
              <span class="ws-check-box">&#9744;</span>
              <div>
                <strong>Terminal</strong> — Your command center.
                <div class="ws-check-why">Use Terminal (macOS), iTerm2, or Windows Terminal.</div>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="ws-check">
              <span class="ws-check-box">&#9744;</span>
              <div>
                <strong>Git</strong> — The AI's "Undo" button.
                <div class="ws-check-why">Claude works best when she can see your project's history.</div>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="ws-check">
              <span class="ws-check-box">&#9744;</span>
              <div>
                <strong>Anthropic Account</strong> — The key to the brain.
                <div class="ws-check-why">Sign up at <a href="https://claude.ai" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">claude.ai</a>.</div>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="ws-code-block">
            <p class="ws-code-label">Step 1 — Install</p>
            <p class="ws-code-note">Copy and paste this into your terminal and press Enter:</p>
            <div class="ws-cmd" data-cmd="npm install -g @anthropic-ai/claude-code">
              <code>npm install -g @anthropic-ai/claude-code</code>
              <button type="button" class="ws-copy" aria-label="Copy install command">Copy</button>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="ws-code-block">
            <p class="ws-code-label">Step 2 — Launch & Login</p>
            <div class="ws-cmd" data-cmd="claude">
              <code>claude</code>
              <button type="button" class="ws-copy" aria-label="Copy launch command">Copy</button>
            </div>
            <p class="ws-code-note">Your browser will open. Log in with your Anthropic account. Then come back here.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- MODULE 01 -->
    <section class="ws-section ws-section--alt">
      <div class="ws-container">
        <p class="ws-section-num">01</p>
        <h2 class="ws-section-title">Shared Memory — giving her a map</h2>
        <p class="ws-principle-tag">Principle: Without a map, the best driver is lost.</p>
        <div class="ws-body">
          <h3>The "Goldfish" Problem</h3>
          <p>Standard chatbots have "goldfish memory"—they forget the context of your project every time you start a new chat. Claude Code solves this with a <strong>Shared Memory</strong> system.</p>
          <p>By creating a <code>CLAUDE.md</code> file, you are writing an "orientation manual" that Claude reads <em>every time</em> you speak to her.</p>

          <div class="ws-exercise">
            <p class="ws-exercise-label">Let's try it — 15 min</p>
            <p>Inside your project (in the Claude terminal), type this command. It tells Claude to look around and create your map:</p>
            <div class="ws-cmd ws-cmd--prompt" data-cmd="/init">
              <code>/init</code>
              <button type="button" class="ws-copy" aria-label="Copy init command">Copy</button>
            </div>
            <p>Once she's done, she will create a <code>CLAUDE.md</code>. Read it. Does it describe your project correctly? If not, ask her: <em>"Update CLAUDE.md to reflect that this is a personal portfolio."</em></p>
          </div>

          <div class="ws-key-insight">
            <strong>Key insight:</strong> <code>CLAUDE.md</code> is the difference between an AI that "guesses" and an AI that "knows." It's where you store your project's soul: its tech stack, its rules, and its goals.
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- MODULE 02 -->
    <section class="ws-section">
      <div class="ws-container">
        <p class="ws-section-num">02</p>
        <h2 class="ws-section-title">Orientation — your first real conversation</h2>
        <p class="ws-principle-tag">Principle: The project needs a visible sense of where things stand now.</p>
        <div class="ws-body">
          <h3>Beyond "Write me a function"</h3>
          <p>Most people use AI to generate snippets. Today, you will use it to <strong>explore</strong>. This is where you test the "Observe" part of the Brain's loop.</p>

          <div class="ws-exercise">
            <p class="ws-exercise-label">Let's try it — 15 min</p>
            <p>Once you are inside Claude Code (by typing <code>claude</code>), try these progressive prompts. Notice how she uses tools to answer:</p>
            <div class="ws-cmd ws-cmd--prompt" data-cmd="Read the project and tell me what you understand about it.">
              <code>Read the project and tell me what you understand about it.</code>
              <button type="button" class="ws-copy" aria-label="Copy prompt">Copy</button>
            </div>
            <div class="ws-cmd ws-cmd--prompt" data-cmd="What are the main folders and how do they connect?">
              <code>What are the main folders and how do they connect?</code>
              <button type="button" class="ws-copy" aria-label="Copy prompt">Copy</button>
            </div>
            <div class="ws-cmd ws-cmd--prompt" data-cmd="If I wanted to change the primary color of the site, where would I look?">
              <code>If I wanted to change the primary color of the site, where would I look?</code>
              <button type="button" class="ws-copy" aria-label="Copy prompt">Copy</button>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="ws-tools-grid">
            <div class="ws-tool"><strong>Read</strong><span>She opens and reads a file.</span></div>
            <div class="ws-tool"><strong>LS</strong><span>She lists files in a folder.</span></div>
            <div class="ws-tool"><strong>Grep</strong><span>She searches for words across all files.</span></div>
          </div>

          <div class="ws-key-insight">
            <strong>Key insight:</strong> You are not just chatting; you are co-navigating. By asking Claude to explain <em>why</em> something is the way it is, you are training her (and yourself) on the project's logic.
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- MODULE 03 -->
    <section class="ws-section ws-section--alt">
      <div class="ws-container">
        <p class="ws-section-num">03</p>
        <h2 class="ws-section-title">Evidence — thinking before doing</h2>
        <p class="ws-principle-tag">Principle: Ideas should be grounded in visible evidence, not assumptions.</p>
        <div class="ws-body">
          <h3>The "Architect" Pause</h3>
          <p>The most common AI mistake: asking for a change before understanding the context. This leads to broken code and frustration.</p>
          <p>We will practice <strong>Evidence Discipline</strong>. We force the AI to show us it understands the current state before we let it change anything.</p>

          <div class="ws-exercise">
            <p class="ws-exercise-label">Let's try it — 20 min</p>
            <p>Pick a file you want to change. Ask Claude to investigate it first:</p>
            <div class="ws-cmd ws-cmd--prompt" data-cmd="Read [file-path] and explain how it handles data.">
              <code>Read [file-path] and explain how it handles data.</code>
              <button type="button" class="ws-copy" aria-label="Copy prompt">Copy</button>
            </div>
            <p>Then, only after she explains it, give the command:</p>
            <div class="ws-cmd ws-cmd--prompt" data-cmd="Based on that understanding, add a new field called 'lastUpdated'.">
              <code>Based on that understanding, add a new field called 'lastUpdated'.</code>
              <button type="button" class="ws-copy" aria-label="Copy prompt">Copy</button>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="ws-key-insight">
            <strong>Key insight:</strong> An AI collaborator will treat an assumption as a fact if you present it as one. The discipline to say "read first, then act" produces dramatically better results.
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- MODULE 04 -->
    <section class="ws-section">
      <div class="ws-container">
        <p class="ws-section-num">04</p>
        <h2 class="ws-section-title">Clarity — permissions and trust</h2>
        <p class="ws-principle-tag">Principle: Good results depend on knowing how to work together well.</p>
        <div class="ws-body">
          <h3>The Safety Brake</h3>
          <p>Claude Code is powerful. She can delete files, run commands, and commit code. To work together safely, we use <strong>Permissions</strong>.</p>

          <div class="ws-exercise">
            <p class="ws-exercise-label">Let's try it — 10 min</p>
            <p>Inside Claude Code, check your current "rules of engagement":</p>
            <div class="ws-cmd ws-cmd--prompt" data-cmd="/permissions">
              <code>/permissions</code>
              <button type="button" class="ws-copy" aria-label="Copy permissions command">Copy</button>
            </div>
            <p>You can choose to approve every single edit (Strict), or let her work autonomously for a session (Loose). </p>
            <p><strong>Pro tip:</strong> Press <code>Shift + Tab</code> while she is working to toggle between "Review mode" and "Auto-accept".</p>
          </div>

          <div class="ws-key-insight">
            <strong>Key insight:</strong> Start strict, loosen as trust builds. This mirrors how you onboard any new team member—you give more autonomy as they prove they understand the context.
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- MODULE 05 -->
    <section class="ws-section ws-section--alt">
      <div class="ws-container">
        <p class="ws-section-num">05</p>
        <h2 class="ws-section-title">Roles — custom agents and commands</h2>
        <p class="ws-principle-tag">Principle: Every collaborator should have a clear role and responsibility.</p>
        <div class="ws-body">
          <h3>The Specialist Squad</h3>
          <p>Claude Code is a generalist. But you can "program" her to be a specialist. By creating custom commands, you design specific roles for the Brain to inhabit.</p>

          <div class="ws-exercise">
            <p class="ws-exercise-label">Let's try it — 20 min</p>
            <p>We will create a <code>/review</code> specialist. In your terminal (outside Claude), run this:</p>
            <div class="ws-cmd" data-cmd="mkdir -p .claude/commands">
              <code>mkdir -p .claude/commands</code>
              <button type="button" class="ws-copy" aria-label="Copy command">Copy</button>
            </div>
            <p>Now, create a file at <code>.claude/commands/review.md</code> and paste this instruction inside it:</p>
            <div class="ws-code-block">
              <pre><code>You are a Senior Reviewer. Look at my current 
changes and find 3 ways to make them cleaner. 
Be direct and brief.</code></pre>
            </div>
            <p>Now go back into Claude and type <code>/review</code>. She will instantly switch from "Builder" to "Senior Reviewer."</p>
          </div>

          <div class="ws-key-insight">
            <strong>Key insight:</strong> Custom commands turn Claude from a general assistant into a team of specialists. One command for testing, one for documentation, one for performance—all living in your terminal.
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- MODULE 06 -->
    <section class="ws-section">
      <div class="ws-container">
        <p class="ws-section-num">06</p>
        <h2 class="ws-section-title">Continuity — memory that persists</h2>
        <p class="ws-principle-tag">Principle: Decisions should be preserved so the team does not restart the thinking.</p>
        <div class="ws-body">
          <h3>Beyond the Session</h3>
          <p>Most AI chats are ephemeral—they disappear when you close the tab. In Claude Code, you can tell the Brain what to <strong>remember</strong> for next time.</p>

          <div class="ws-exercise">
            <p class="ws-exercise-label">Let's try it — 15 min</p>
            <p>Tell Claude a preference and ask her to remember it:</p>
            <div class="ws-cmd ws-cmd--prompt" data-cmd="We always use functional components here. Remember this preference.">
              <code>We always use functional components here. Remember this preference.</code>
              <button type="button" class="ws-copy" aria-label="Copy prompt">Copy</button>
            </div>
            <p>Now, clear your chat with <code>/clear</code> and ask her: <em>"What are our project preferences?"</em> She will recall it from her persistent memory.</p>
          </div>

          <div class="ws-key-insight">
            <strong>Key insight:</strong> The biggest failure in AI projects is losing context. By using persistent memory, you ensure that every session starts with the wisdom of the last one.
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- MODULE 07 -->
    <section class="ws-section ws-section--alt">
      <div class="ws-container">
        <p class="ws-section-num">07</p>
        <h2 class="ws-section-title">Awareness — connecting the world</h2>
        <p class="ws-principle-tag">Principle: Both humans and AI need to know what materials exist.</p>
        <div class="ws-body">
          <h3>The Model Context Protocol (MCP)</h3>
          <p>Claude Code can see more than just your files. She can see your Google Calendar, your GitHub issues, or your database. This is possible through <strong>MCP</strong>.</p>

          <div class="ws-exercise">
            <p class="ws-exercise-label">Let's try it — 15 min</p>
            <p>Inside Claude, open the settings to see what she can connect to:</p>
            <div class="ws-cmd ws-cmd--prompt" data-cmd="/settings">
              <code>/settings</code>
              <button type="button" class="ws-copy" aria-label="Copy settings command">Copy</button>
            </div>
            <p>Imagine connecting her to your team's Slack or your project's Trello. She becomes an agent that knows the <strong>business context</strong>, not just the code.</p>
          </div>

          <div class="ws-key-insight">
            <strong>Key insight:</strong> MCP turns Claude from a "coding tool" into a "workspace agent." She becomes aware of the assets that exist outside the terminal.
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- MODULE 08 -->
    <section class="ws-section">
      <div class="ws-container">
        <p class="ws-section-num">08</p>
        <h2 class="ws-section-title">Orchestration — the big goal</h2>
        <p class="ws-principle-tag">Principle: Workflows that work well should be saved, refined, and reused.</p>
        <div class="ws-body">
          <h3>The Orchestrator's Moment</h3>
          <p>This is where it all comes together. You aren't asking for a function. You are asking for a <strong>result</strong>.</p>

          <div class="ws-exercise">
            <p class="ws-exercise-label">The Finale — 30 min</p>
            <p>Pick a real feature you've wanted to build. Give the full context:</p>
            <div class="ws-cmd ws-cmd--prompt" data-cmd="Read the project first. Plan a new 'Contact Me' page with a form. Then implement it and add a commit when you are done.">
              <code>Read the project first. Plan a new 'Contact Me' page with a form. Then implement it and add a commit when you are done.</code>
              <button type="button" class="ws-copy" aria-label="Copy prompt">Copy</button>
            </div>
            <p>Watch the Brain's loop in action: <strong>Observe</strong> (read files) &rarr; <strong>Think</strong> (plan the page) &rarr; <strong>Act</strong> (write code) &rarr; <strong>Reflect</strong> (check for errors).</p>
          </div>

          <div class="ws-key-insight">
            <strong>Key insight:</strong> Orchestration is the ultimate skill. It's when you stop doing the work and start <strong>directing</strong> the work.
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- MODULE 09 -->
    <section class="ws-section ws-section--alt">
      <div class="ws-container">
        <p class="ws-section-num">09</p>
        <h2 class="ws-section-title">The Future — what's next?</h2>
        <div class="ws-body">
          <p>You've gone from zero to Orchestrator. But this is just the beginning. The future of software isn't just "AI-assisted"; it is **AI-native**.</p>
          <ul class="ws-future-list">
            <li><strong>Autonomous Teams:</strong> Agents that handle bug fixes and documentation while you sleep.</li>
            <li><strong>Project Intelligence:</strong> Every team member has an AI peer that knows the entire history of the project.</li>
            <li><strong>Natural Interface:</strong> Coding becomes a conversation about intent, not just syntax.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- CLOSING -->
    <section class="ws-section">
      <div class="ws-container">
        <h2 class="ws-section-title">You've designed a mind.</h2>
        <div class="ws-body">
          <p>You did not just learn a tool today. You built an environment where your mind and an AI's brain can think together naturally.</p>
          <p>This is <strong>Project Intelligence</strong>.</p>

          <div class="ws-cta-block">
            <p>Want to bring this workshop to your team or organization?</p>
            <div class="ws-cta-row">
              <a href="https://www.linkedin.com/in/pablosuzarte/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="ws-cta">Get in touch with Pablo &rarr;</a>
              <a href="/how-i-build-with-ai" class="ws-cta ws-cta--secondary">&larr; Back to AI School</a>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>
  </article>
</main>

  <style>
    /* OpenClaw-inspired "Terminal-Core" palette */
    .ws {
      --cl-bg: #000000;
      --cl-surface: #0a0a0a;
      --cl-surface-2: #111111;
      --cl-border: #222222;
      --cl-accent: #FF4500; /* OpenClaw Vibrant Orange-Red */
      --cl-accent-soft: rgba(255, 69, 0, 0.1);
      --cl-accent-glow: rgba(255, 69, 0, 0.25);
      --cl-text: #FFFFFF;
      --cl-muted: #888888;
      --cl-code: #EDEDED;
      --font-mono: 'JetBrains Mono', 'Fira Code', monospace;
      --font-sans: 'Manrope', system-ui, sans-serif;
      color: var(--cl-text);
      font-family: var(--font-sans);
      background: var(--cl-bg);
    }

    .ws-nav {
      position: fixed; top: 0; left: 0; right: 0; z-index: 100;
      backdrop-filter: blur(12px); -webkit-backdrop-filter: blur(12px);
      background: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.8); border-bottom: 1px solid var(--cl-border);
    }
    .ws-nav-inner {
      max-width: 1000px; margin: 0 auto; padding: 0.75rem 2rem;
      display: flex; align-items: center; gap: 1.5rem;
    }
    .nav-back { color: var(--cl-muted); text-decoration: none; font-size: 0.8rem; font-weight: 600; text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.05em; transition: color 0.2s; }
    .nav-back:hover { color: var(--cl-accent); }
    .nav-logo { font-weight: 900; font-size: 1.25rem; letter-spacing: -0.05em; color: var(--cl-text); text-decoration: none; }
    .nav-breadcrumb { color: var(--cl-muted); font-size: 0.7rem; font-weight: 700; letter-spacing: 0.1em; text-transform: uppercase; margin-left: auto; border: 1px solid var(--cl-border); padding: 0.25rem 0.6rem; border-radius: 4px; }

    .ws {
      padding-top: 4rem;
      min-height: 100vh;
    }
    .ws-container { max-width: 900px; margin: 0 auto; padding: 0 2rem; }

    .ws-hero { padding: 6rem 0 4rem; border-bottom: 1px solid var(--cl-border); text-align: center; }
    .ws-kicker { font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: 0.75rem; font-weight: 600; letter-spacing: 0.1em; text-transform: uppercase; color: var(--cl-accent); margin-bottom: 1.5rem; }
    .ws-kicker::before { content: "[ "; }
    .ws-kicker::after { content: " ]"; }
    .ws-title { font-size: clamp(2.5rem, 8vw, 4.5rem); font-weight: 900; line-height: 1; letter-spacing: -0.05em; color: var(--cl-text); margin-bottom: 1.5rem; text-transform: uppercase; }
    .ws-subtitle { font-size: clamp(1.1rem, 2.5vw, 1.5rem); color: var(--cl-muted); line-height: 1.4; max-width: 650px; margin: 0 auto 3rem; }

    .ws-meta-row { display: grid; grid-template-columns: repeat(4, 1fr); gap: 1px; background: var(--cl-border); border: 1px solid var(--cl-border); }
    .ws-meta-item { padding: 1.5rem; background: var(--cl-bg); }
    .ws-meta-label { display: block; font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: 0.65rem; font-weight: 700; text-transform: uppercase; color: var(--cl-muted); margin-bottom: 0.5rem; }
    .ws-meta-value { display: block; font-size: 0.9rem; font-weight: 800; color: var(--cl-text); text-transform: uppercase; }

    .ws-section { padding: 6rem 0; border-bottom: 1px solid var(--cl-border); }
    .ws-section--alt { background: var(--cl-surface); }
    .ws-section-num { font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700; color: var(--cl-muted); margin-bottom: 1rem; display: block; }
    .ws-section-title { font-size: clamp(1.75rem, 5vw, 2.75rem); font-weight: 900; letter-spacing: -0.04em; color: var(--cl-text); margin-bottom: 2rem; line-height: 1.1; text-transform: uppercase; }
    .ws-section-title::before { content: "⟩ "; color: var(--cl-accent); font-family: var(--font-mono); }
    
    .ws-principle-tag { font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: 0.8rem; color: var(--cl-accent); background: var(--cl-accent-soft); padding: 0.5rem 1rem; border-radius: 4px; display: inline-block; margin-bottom: 2.5rem; }

    .ws-body { color: var(--cl-text); font-size: 1.1rem; line-height: 1.6; }
    .ws-body p { margin-bottom: 1.5rem; }
    .ws-body h3 { font-size: 1.25rem; font-weight: 900; color: var(--cl-text); margin: 3rem 0 1rem; text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: -0.02em; }
    .ws-body h3::before { content: "// "; color: var(--cl-muted); }
    .ws-body strong { color: var(--cl-text); font-weight: 800; border-bottom: 2px solid var(--cl-accent); }
    
    .ws-intro-grid { display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1.2fr 0.8fr; gap: 4rem; align-items: center; }
    .ws-intro-card { background: var(--cl-surface-2); padding: 2rem; border-radius: 4px; border: 1px solid var(--cl-border); }
    .ws-intro-card h3 { font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: 0.75rem; text-transform: uppercase; color: var(--cl-muted); margin-bottom: 1.5rem; border-bottom: 1px solid var(--cl-border); padding-bottom: 0.75rem; }
    .ws-intro-card h3::before { content: ""; }
    .ws-trans-step { font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: 0.85rem; padding: 1rem; display: flex; align-items: center; gap: 1rem; color: var(--cl-muted); border: 1px solid transparent; }
    .ws-trans-step span { font-weight: 800; color: var(--cl-muted); }
    .ws-trans-step--active { background: var(--cl-bg); color: var(--cl-text); border-color: var(--cl-border); }
    .ws-trans-step--active span { color: var(--cl-accent); }
    .ws-trans-arrow { padding-left: 2rem; color: var(--cl-accent); font-family: var(--font-mono); font-weight: 900; }

    .ws-brain-loop { display: grid; grid-template-columns: repeat(4, 1fr); gap: 1px; background: var(--cl-border); border: 1px solid var(--cl-border); margin: 3rem 0; }
    .ws-loop-node { padding: 1.5rem; background: var(--cl-bg); text-align: left; }
    .ws-loop-node strong { display: block; color: var(--cl-accent); font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: 0.75rem; text-transform: uppercase; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; border: none; }
    .ws-loop-node span { font-size: 0.85rem; color: var(--cl-muted); line-height: 1.4; display: block; }

    .ws-checklist { display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: 1px; background: var(--cl-border); border: 1px solid var(--cl-border); margin: 2rem 0; }
    .ws-check { display: flex; gap: 1.5rem; padding: 1.25rem; background: var(--cl-bg); align-items: flex-start; }
    .ws-check-box { font-family: var(--font-mono); color: var(--cl-accent); font-weight: 900; }
    .ws-check-why { font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: 0.75rem; color: var(--cl-muted); margin-top: 0.5rem; }
    .ws-check code { background: var(--cl-surface-2); padding: 0.2rem 0.4rem; border-radius: 3px; color: var(--cl-code); }

    .ws-exercise { margin: 4rem 0; padding: 3rem; background: var(--cl-surface); border: 1px solid var(--cl-border); position: relative; }
    .ws-exercise::before { content: "EXERCISE"; position: absolute; top: -10px; left: 20px; background: var(--cl-bg); padding: 0 10px; font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: 0.7rem; color: var(--cl-accent); border: 1px solid var(--cl-border); }
    .ws-exercise-label { font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: 0.75rem; font-weight: 800; color: var(--cl-muted); margin-bottom: 1.5rem; display: block; }

    .ws-code-block { margin: 2rem 0; background: #000; border: 1px solid var(--cl-border); border-radius: 4px; }
    .ws-code-label { font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: 0.65rem; color: var(--cl-muted); padding: 0.75rem 1rem; border-bottom: 1px solid var(--cl-border); text-transform: uppercase; }
    .ws-code-block pre { padding: 1.5rem; overflow-x: auto; margin: 0; }
    .ws-code-block code { font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: 0.9rem; color: var(--cl-code); line-height: 1.6; }
    .ws-code-note { font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: 0.75rem; color: var(--cl-muted); padding: 1rem; border-top: 1px solid var(--cl-border); }

    .ws-cmd {
      display: flex; align-items: center; justify-content: space-between; gap: 1rem;
      padding: 1rem 1.25rem;
      background: #000; border: 1px solid var(--cl-border); border-radius: 4px;
      margin: 1rem 0; cursor: pointer; transition: border-color 0.2s;
    }
    .ws-cmd:hover { border-color: var(--cl-accent); }
    .ws-cmd:focus-within { outline: 2px solid var(--cl-accent); outline-offset: 4px; }
    .ws-cmd code { font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: 0.95rem; color: var(--cl-text); flex: 1; }
    .ws-cmd::before { content: "$ "; color: var(--cl-muted); font-family: var(--font-mono); }
    .ws-cmd--prompt::before { content: "⟩ "; color: var(--cl-accent); }

    .ws-copy {
      flex-shrink: 0; padding: 0.5rem 0.75rem; border: 1px solid var(--cl-border);
      border-radius: 4px; background: var(--cl-surface-2); color: var(--cl-muted); font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: 0.7rem;
      font-weight: 700; text-transform: uppercase; cursor: pointer; transition: all 0.2s;
    }
    .ws-copy:hover { color: var(--cl-text); border-color: var(--cl-text); }
    .ws-copy.ws-copied { color: #000; background: var(--cl-accent); border-color: var(--cl-accent); }

    .ws-tools-grid { display: grid; grid-template-columns: repeat(3, 1fr); gap: 1px; background: var(--cl-border); border: 1px solid var(--cl-border); margin: 3rem 0; }
    .ws-tool { padding: 1.5rem; background: var(--cl-bg); }
    .ws-tool strong { display: block; font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: 0.8rem; color: var(--cl-accent); margin-bottom: 0.5rem; border: none; }
    .ws-tool span { font-size: 0.85rem; color: var(--cl-muted); line-height: 1.4; }

    .ws-future-list { display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: 1rem; margin: 3rem 0; }
    .ws-future-list li { padding: 1.5rem; background: var(--cl-surface-2); border: 1px solid var(--cl-border); border-radius: 4px; font-size: 1rem; position: relative; padding-left: 3rem; }
    .ws-future-list li::before { content: "⟩"; position: absolute; left: 1.25rem; color: var(--cl-accent); font-family: var(--font-mono); font-weight: 900; }
    .ws-future-list strong { color: var(--cl-text); display: inline; border: none; margin-right: 0.5rem; }

    .ws-key-insight { margin: 3rem 0; padding: 2rem; background: var(--cl-surface); border: 1px solid var(--cl-accent); border-radius: 4px; font-size: 1rem; position: relative; }
    .ws-key-insight::after { content: "!"; position: absolute; top: -12px; right: 20px; background: var(--cl-accent); color: #000; width: 24px; height: 24px; display: flex; align-items: center; justify-content: center; font-weight: 900; border-radius: 50%; }

    .ws-cta-block { margin-top: 6rem; padding: 4rem; background: var(--cl-surface-2); border: 1px solid var(--cl-border); text-align: center; }
    .ws-cta-block p { font-size: 1.25rem; color: var(--cl-muted); margin-bottom: 3rem; font-weight: 600; }
    .ws-cta { display: inline-flex; padding: 1.25rem 2.5rem; background: #FFFFFF; color: #000000; font-weight: 900; font-size: 1rem; border-radius: 4px; text-decoration: none; text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.05em; transition: all 0.2s; }
    .ws-cta:hover { background: var(--cl-accent); color: #000; transform: translateY(-2px); }
    .ws-cta--secondary { background: transparent; color: #FFFFFF; border: 1px solid #FFFFFF; margin-left: 1rem; }
    .ws-cta--secondary:hover { background: #FFFFFF; color: #000; }
    .ws-cta-row { display: flex; gap: 1.5rem; justify-content: center; flex-wrap: wrap; }

    @media (max-width: 768px) {
      .ws-intro-grid { grid-template-columns: 1fr; gap: 2rem; }
      .ws-brain-loop { grid-template-columns: repeat(2, 1fr); }
      .ws-tools-grid { grid-template-columns: 1fr; }
      .ws-meta-row { grid-template-columns: repeat(2, 1fr); }
      .ws-hero { padding: 4rem 0; }
      .ws-cta-row { flex-direction: column; }
      .ws-cta--secondary { margin-left: 0; }
    }
  </style>

  <script is:inline>
    document.querySelectorAll('.ws-copy').forEach(btn => {
      btn.addEventListener('click', (e) => {
        e.stopPropagation()
        const container = btn.closest('.ws-cmd')
        const text = container ? container.dataset.cmd : ''
        if (!text) return
        navigator.clipboard.writeText(text.replace(/&#10;/g, '\n')).then(() => {
          btn.textContent = 'Copied!'
          btn.classList.add('ws-copied')
          setTimeout(() => {
            btn.textContent = 'Copy'
            btn.classList.remove('ws-copied')
          }, 2000)
        })
      })
    })
    // Click anywhere on the command block to copy too
    document.querySelectorAll('.ws-cmd:not(.ws-cmd--multi)').forEach(cmd => {
      cmd.addEventListener('click', () => {
        cmd.querySelector('.ws-copy')?.click()
      })
    })
  </script>
</Layout>
